posts.name: Elliot Scher
posts.cooked: No, this thread says it’s not a good idea to change the thread priority when using AdvantageKit. We’ve configured the main thread to run with real-time priority, though not the highest priority. The risks of doing this are described briefly in the AdvantageKit documentation, which is why we generally do not recommend this approach: This can severely affect the performance of multiple background threads. Vendors are one concern, but it also affects NetworkTables, AdvantageKit, and threads created in user code. We’ve done extensive testing to ensure that these background threads have sufficient priority and don’t interfere with critical functions.

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked: The issue does not appear to stem from the autochooser itself. The autochooser loads all paths during the initialization of the RobotContainer, which is unlikely to cause loop overruns when enabled. While you were unsure about adjusting thread priority, I recommend testing it if you have the opportunity before your next competition. We found that increasing thread priority helped eliminate almost all loop overruns in our tests. However, if your cycle times remain close to 20 milliseconds or you notice symptoms such as stale CAN frames or issues with odometry not updating, reverting to the previous configuration might be necessary.

posts.name: Todd
posts.cooked: It's weird, though, that so much time is unaccounted for by Tracer; the 'UserCodeMS' timer in advantagekit’s overridden main loop seems pretty concrete. While it's worse at the start of autonomous, there are recurring long loops through the rest of autonomous, and even into teleop, none of which Tracer doesn’t flag any significant delays in, despite noticeable spikes in processing time (20-40ms overruns, based on my observations). This makes me cautious about assuming that paths are being regenerated, especially since your code appears to be functioning properly. Adding a print statement would help verify whether commands generated in your AutonomousCommands.java function are indeed being called during disabled mode when selected in the dashboard. The Advantagekit timing in ‘Logger’ effectively accounts for additional processes inserted between cycles, and these don’t appear to contribute significantly to the ~150ms overruns observed in FullCycleMS. This discrepancy is quite puzzling. If I were in your position, I’d probably start by disabling the Logger during autonomous to see if Tracer still triggers alerts.
